23 SECTION 3.(a) Transition from Licenses to Certifications. – The following
24 provisions shall govern the transition from natural hair care specialist licenses previously
25 required for practice under Chapter 88B of the General Statutes to infection control certifications
26 for natural hair care specialists under this act:
27 (1) Automatic conversion. – All individuals holding valid natural hair care
28 specialist licenses issued by the North Carolina Board of Cosmetic Art
29 Examiners as of October 1, 2026, shall automatically be deemed to hold the
30 equivalent infection control certification under Chapter 88B of the General
31 Statutes, as amended by this act, without further examination, application,
32 fees, or additional qualification requirements. The Board shall provide any
33 individual who is deemed to hold an infection control certification under this
34 subsection with an infection control certification free of charge.
35 (2) Pending applications. – Notwithstanding any other provision of law, any
36 application for a natural hair care specialist license submitted to the Board
37 prior to October 1, 2026, and still pending on that date shall be granted as an
38 infection control certification if the applicant meets all of the following
39 requirements:
40 a. Successful completion of at least 300 hours of a natural hair care
41 curriculum in an approved cosmetic art school.
42 b. Payment of the fees required by G.S. 88B-20.
43 SECTION 3.(b) Transition from Apprentice Licenses to Cosmetologist Licenses. –
44 The following provisions shall govern the transition from apprentice licenses previously required
45 for practice under Chapter 88B of the General Statutes to cosmetologist licenses under this act:
46 (1) Automatic conversion. – All individuals holding apprentice licenses issued by
47 the North Carolina Board of Cosmetic Art Examiners as of October 1, 2026,
48 shall automatically be deemed to hold a cosmetologist license without further
49 examination, application, fees, or additional qualification requirements.
50 (2) Pending applications. – Notwithstanding any other provision of law, any
51 application for an apprentice license submitted to the Board prior to October
Page 12 Senate Bill 808-Third Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 1, 2026, and still pending on that date shall be granted as a cosmetologist
2 license if the applicant meets all of the following requirements:
3 a. Successful completion of at least 1,200 hours of a cosmetology
4 curriculum in an approved cosmetic art school.
5 b. Passage of an examination conducted by the Board.
6 c. Payment of the fees required by G.S. 88B-20.
7 (3) Renewal of licenses. – Upon expiration of an apprentice license, the Board
8 shall permit individuals to renew their credential as a cosmetologist license
9 without resubmission or additional qualifications.
10 SECTION 3.(c) Rulemaking. – The North Carolina Board of Cosmetic Art
11 Examiners shall adopt rules to implement the provisions of this act. The Board shall prominently
12 post on its publicly available website information about all of the following:
13 (1) The elimination of the apprentice license and transition to cosmetologist
14 licensure.
15 (2) The elimination of the natural hair care specialist license and transition to
16 certification.
17 (3) The requirement for completion of the infection control course for newly
18 certified natural hair care specialists.
19 (4) Clear instructions for accessing at least one free Board-approved infection
20 control course that satisfies the requirements for infection control certification
21 for natural hair care specialists.
22 SECTION 3.(d) Rulemaking. – The North Carolina Board of Barber and Electrolysis
23 Examiners may adopt rules to implement Section 2 of this act.
24 SECTION 4. Sections 1 and 2 of this act become effective October 1, 2026. The
25 remainder of this act is effective when it becomes law.
